T1  - Credibility and the dynamics of disinflation in open economies A note on the southern cone experiments
AU  - Lächler, Ulrich
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
SP  - 285
EP  - 307
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/05/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(88)90001-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387888900016
AB  - When people lack confidence in the ability of politicians to carry out a newly announced disinflationary policy, disinflation becomes more difficult to achieve. Numerous writers have emphasized the importance of policy consistency for establishing credibility. This essay suggests, in addition, that policies with a quicker disinflationary impact become more credible sooner, and thus have a better chance of succeeding. With that proposition in mind, the objective is to examine and compare the initial impacts of alternative disinflationary strategies in an open economy with capital mobility, using evidence from the Southern Cone experience with preannounced exchange rates for illustrative purposes.
