T1  - The wage-goods constraint on a developing economy: Theory and evidence
AU  - Dutta, Jayasri
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 28
IS  - 3
SP  - 341
EP  - 363
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/05/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(88)90004-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387888900041
AB  - In a dual economy, the traditional, or agricultural sector generally has a relatively low supply response to prices. If, in addition, the real wages of the modern, or industrial sector are denominated at least partly in terms of the product of agriculture, then agricultural output sets an upper bound on employment in industry. Such a constraint may be binding in the short run, whenever the level of food production is low. This is called the ‘wage-goods constraint’. This paper examines the analytics of a wage-goods constraint in the framework of a two-commodity model of a dual economy, with surplus labor, where (unconstrained) industrial output is demand-determined. The effects of either expansionary or redistributive policy may be quite different, and sometimes perverse, in a situation where the wage-goods constraint is binding. Next, data for the Indian economy is used to test the hypothesis that the wage-goods constraint was binding in the Indian industrial sector between the years 1955 to 1980. The results indicate that this was the case for most of the period.
ER  - 

